<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Icelandic Plane Arrives in Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 25 (Xinhua)-- An Icelandic private plane
carrying gifts and medicine for the Iraqi people arrived at
al-Happaniya military airport near Baghdad this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
This is the second foreign flight to Iraq in two days, which had
been approved by U.N. sanctions committee.
</P>
<P>
A Russian plane carrying tonnes of medicines arrived in Baghdad
on Thursday, on board of which were also a group of members of the
Liberal Democratic Party opposing sanctions against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The gifts and medicine of the Icelandic plane had been
presented from the Reykjavik-based Humanitarian Academy of Peace
2000 Institute, in cooperation with an Italian organization called
Bridge to Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
President of the institute, Thor Magnusson, told reporters upon
arrival in Baghdad that the flight was aimed to a call on the
international organizations to work for the lifting of the embargo
imposed on Iraq for more than seven years now.
</P>
<P>
The air flight was accompanied by a delegation from the
Icelandic institute, a journalist from Iceland TV, three members
of the Italian organization Bridge to Baghdad and a photographer.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. sanctions against Iraq, which also include an air
flight ban, will not be lifted until Iraq have been approved that
it had eliminated all its weapons of mass destruction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
