<HEADLINE> Aid Flights to Iraq to Continue: Russian Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 26 (Xinhua) -- Flights will continue
until the embargo on Iraq is lifted, said the head of a Russian
party delegation in Baghdad today.
</P>
<P>
Michael Kostotiken, head of a delegation of the Russian Liberal
Democratic Party made the remarks when meeting with Chairman of
the Iraqi National Assembly (parliament) Sadoun Hammadi.
</P>
<P>
The Russian official came to Baghdad with a delegation of 14
members aboard a Russian plane which arrived in Baghdad Thursday
in attempt to break the U.N. air flight ban imposed after Iraq
invaded Kuwait in 1990, the official Iraqi News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The Russian plane has brought five tonnes of medicine and
medical appliances to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Kostotiken, also a member of the Russian
Duma (lower house of parliament), expressed the happiness for
carrying out this humanitarian flight for the Iraqi children.
</P>
<P>
He also conveyed greetings from the Chairman of the Liberal
Democratic Party Vladimir Zhirinovsky and Duma members to the
Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, Hammadi lauded the solidarity step represented
by the coming of the Russian aid plane to Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
The plane was stopped by Iran on Tuesday as Iran said "sending
the cargo through air would only be possible through special
U.N. authorization."
</P>
<P>
After receiving permission from the United Nations, the plane
landed at Saddam international airport, which saw the first
foreign flight since January 16, 1991 when it received the last
foreign aircraft.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, Hammadi called for the lifting of the
seven-year-old U.N. embargo on Iraq as soon as possible and
putting an end to the American hegemony over the activities of the
U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) on eliminating Iraq's weapons of
mass destruction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
