<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Denies Three-way Meeting with Arafat, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 26 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu denied today that he would hold a three-way
meeting with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and American
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright next month.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu was commenting on a media report which quoted senior
Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat as saying that the three-way
meeting would take place in Washington next month, when Netanyahu
and Arafat are scheduled to meet American President Bill Clinton
separately.
</P>
<P>
But Erekat said no date had yet been set for the
Netanyahu-Arafat-Albright meeting.
</P>
<P>
Clinton intends to push forward the Israeli-Palestinian peace
process, which has been stalled over Israel's delay in carrying
out the second troop redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Cabinet has been holding inner consultations on
mapping out the percentage of the pullback and guidelines on the
final-status talks with the Palestinian National Authority. The
United States is demanding Israel to come out with a final decision
by January 15, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government is proposing creating two security zones
along the 1949 armistice line and the Jordan Valley in order to
protect its safety.
</P>
<P>
Due to big differences between the hardliners and moderates, no
consensus has been achieved despite the intensive deliberations
held within the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
In a message delivered on Christmas day in the West Bank city
of Bethlehem, Arafat said he would present Clinton with a
comprehensive plan on reviving the peace process. He reminded
Israel that the important thing is not forgetting the reactions
from the other side.
</P>
<P>
Israel's state television Channel I also reported today that
Arafat plans to call for deploying international peace-keeping
forces along so-call Israeli security zones. 
</P>
</TEXT>
