<HEADLINE> Britain Offers Loan to Stave Off Crisis in S.Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 26 (Xinhua) -- Britain is to give 300 million
pounds (480 million US dollars) to South Korea as part of an
international emergency package to shore up its collapsing
financial markets.
</P>
<P>
The loan was agreed upon at a meeting between Chancellor Gordon
Brown and Bank of England governor Eddie George to discuss the
crisis on Christmas Eve, according to a Daily Mail report today.
</P>
<P>
Britain is one of the 13 industrial nations which have agreed
to provide 5 billion pounds (8 billion US dollars) by early next
month to help the South Korean economy meet short-term debts after
drastic falls in its currency and share prices.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the International Monetary Fund (IMF) says it will
send an additional 1.5 billion pounds (2.4 billion US dollars) to
South Korea before the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
IMF officials said the 6.5 billion pound (10.4 billion US
dollar) international package assembled by the fund should help
keep the country's economic crisis from developing into a
"serious" recession.
</P>
<P>
The Asian crisis has sparked fears in Britain that the turmoil
could hit job-creating Far Eastern investment.
</P>
<P>
British economic analysts have expressed fears of an imminent
default on South Korea's foreign debt, which is estimated at
around 140 billion pounds (224 billion US dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
