<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment in Vietnam Declines in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, December 26 (Xinhua) -- Foreign investment in Vietnam in
1997 declined in comparison with that in the previous year with a
15 percent reduction in the number of projects and a 37 percent
drop in investment capital.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's Planning and Investment Minister Tran Xuan Gia
attributed the causes of the decline to several factors.
</P>
<P>
The first thing to be blamed is the policy which encourages
foreign investment in far-off regions and requires a greater
proportion of export volume of their product and greater capital
contribution by local partners in joint venture projects.
</P>
<P>
In addition, investors are discouraged to invest in hotel and
office complex development projects, which accounted for 40
percent of the total investment in the country in previous years.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investors also face such obstacles as high land rents
and site clearance fees as well as difficulties in currency
exchanges.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, they also have to spend an excessive amount of
time in conducting surveys to map out investment plans due to the
lack of master development plans in the country.
</P>
<P>
The current monetary crisis in the Southeast Asia also shed
negative impact on the domestic investment environment.
</P>
<P>
Minister Gia said Vietnamese government will make important
decisions soon to improve the investment climate in the country.
</P>
<P>
According to Vietnam news agency, Vietnam extended a total of
foreign investment licenses to 313 foreign invested projects and
allowed 137 others to increase their investment capital in 1997,
bringing foreign investment capital in the country this year to
over 5 billion U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The South Korea tops the list of foreign investors in
Vietnam. Japan, France, Singapore and Thailand follow behind.
</P>
<P>
The cities of Ho Chi Minh and Hanoi have taken lead in terms of
the absorption of investment capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
