<HEADLINE> US Retailing Industry Disappointing for Holidays </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 26 (Xinhua) -- With stores still filled with
holiday goods, U.S. merchants set out today to make up for
after-Christmas sales by offering deep discounts.
</P>
<P>
Retailers and analysts who watch the holiday sales estimated
that sales in stores open at least one year rose a scant 2 percent
to 3 percent in December from a year earlier -- half the gain some
analysts had been expecting, according to a report of the New York
Times today.
</P>
<P>
This lackluster performance was the third in a row for
retailers, despite the strength of the American economy and gains
in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
Stores have carried ads or distributed coupons announcing
bargains on everything from clothes to electronic gadgets, with
discounts running as high as 70 percent. They are betting on a
surge of buying after Christmas.
</P>
<P>
From big retailers like Sears and Macy's to small shops,
merchants opened early this morning and cut prices to get shoppers
into the buying mood.
</P>
<P>
Despite a booming U.S. economy and high consumer confidence,
the holidays failed to meet the expectations of many retailers.
</P>
<P>
Even where sales were strong, profit margins were often weak.
"It took stores years to lean that Easter had disappeared as a
selling holiday," a retail analyst was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Two years ago, retailers reported dismal sales, while 1996 was
a mixed bag.
</P>
<P>
The last blockbuster Christmas for retailers was 1992, when
the biggest merchants' sales rose 8 percent over the previous
year as the economy strengthened, according to the report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
