<HEADLINE> Mozambique's Ruling Party Accused of Playing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, December 26 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican National Resistant
Movement (Renamo) leader Afonoso Dhlakama said today the ruling
Mozambican Liberation Front (Frelimo) is playing "Satonic trick"
to win votes for next year's election.
</P>
<P>
Dhlakama made the accusation here in his Christmas speech to
the whole nation, according to the Mozambican News Agency today.
</P>
<P>
He charged that Frelimo is buying over voters for the local
election to be held on May 29 next year, coining and printing
ballots, in order to fool the international community.
</P>
<P>
Frelimo fully knows, he said, that it will be beaten squarely
during the election through fair and democratic polls.
</P>
<P>
But Dhlakama's statement was dismissed by Manuel Tome, General
Secretary of Frelimo as "groundless" aimed at defaming the entire
process of the local election.
</P>
<P>
Tome said Dhlakama started to talk about the so-called tricks
months before the last election in 1994 and that he is imagining
Frelimo's coining of the ballots this time.
</P>
<P>
Renamo is the mainstream opposition party in the country. It
had fought with Frelimo in a civil war soon after Portugal
granted the country independence in 1975.
</P>
<P>
In October 1992, this armed group was recognized into a legal
party after a peace agreement it signed with the ruling Frelimo
party. 
</P>
</TEXT>
