<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 5 Million Ethiopian Children Suffer From Vitamin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, December 26 (xinhua) -- Some five million
Ethiopian children suffer from Vitamin A deficiency, the
Ethiopian News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Worede-Work Belayneh, an expert of the ministry of health,
said about one percent of the total population of Ethiopia suffer
from Bitot's Spots, an eye disease caused by Vitamin A
deficiency.
</P>
<P>
A recent study conducted jointly by the United Nations
Children's Fund (unicef) and the Family Health Department of the
ministry reveals that three percent of the population in the
northern Tigray Region are victims of Bitot's Spots. The figure
for the east Hararge Region is 7.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The study discloses that severe deficiency of Vitamin A can
also cause irreversible corneal damage, leading to partial or
total blindness.
</P>
<P>
It shows that supplementation of Vitamin A capsules that cost
only two cents each reduces the risk of death of a child
deficient in Vitamin A by 23 percent.
</P>
<P>
Provision of vitamin a capsules can also reduce pregnancy
related deaths by an average of 44 percent among women in areas
where the deficiency is wide spread, the study shows.
</P>
<P>
Worede-Work said the Ministry of Health has drawn short,
medium and long term strategies with a view to curb the effects
of Vitamin A deficiency in the country.
</P>
<P>
Fish liver oil, liver, butter, kidney, egg and milk are among
food stuffs that are rich in Vitamin A, according to the expert.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
