<DOCNO> XIE19971227.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Government Justifies Kaunda's Arrest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 26 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government today
took time to explain to diplomatic missions to the country the
reasons behind the arrest and detention of former president
Kenneth Kaunda, according to Zambia News Agency ZANA.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Affairs Minister Keli Walubita told heads of foreign
missions this afternoon in the capital that Kaunda, also leader
of the country's biggest opposition United National Independence
Party, has been detained as part of the investigations into the
failed October 28 coup.
</P>
<P>
He explained that prior to the abortive military coup designed
to overthrow the incumbent government, Kaunda had been advocating
civil disobedience and violence.
</P>
<P>
Walubita added that in view of this, it is not surprising that
Kaunda has been picked up.
</P>
<P>
He also assured the diplomats that the government will
continue its dialogue with the country's opposition parties and
that the inter-party talks for national harmony will proceed as
planned.
</P>
<P>
The government can not afford to waste all the efforts that
have been put into the preparations of the coming talks, which
aims to break the country's political impasse over, among other
issues, electional provisions in the constitution, said the
foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda was arrested and detained by police on Thursday at his
residence in Lusaka four days after he returned home from a world
tour to lobby the international community to freeze aid to
Zambia.
</P>
<P>
The 73 year-old veteran statesman was served with a 28-day
detention order under the state of emergency declared by
President Frederick Chiluba one day after the failed coup while
the police did not give the reasons for his detention.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda, who is said to be sharing a cell with 30 other
inmates, refused to eat anything after his detention and he said
that he will continue with the hunger strike until he is
furnished with reasons for his detention.
</P>
<P>
He told the country's Human Rights Commission which visited
him at Kamwala Remand Prison that the hunger strike is the "only
weapon" he has to press his freedom and rights, according to
ZANA.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda, father figure of the nation who led Zambia to
independence from British colonial rule in 1964, ruled Zambia for
27 years and was defeated in the country's multi-party elections.
In the second democratic elections held in 1996, he was
disqualified to compete because of his foreign parentage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
