<HEADLINE> Le Pen Condemned by Court for Remarks Over Gas Chamber </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 26 (Xinhua) -- President of the extreme-right
National Front (FN) Jean-Marie Le Pen was condemned today in a
summary procedure by a court in Nanterre near Paris for declaring
on December 5 in Germany that the gas chambers were only a
"detail in the history of World War II."
</P>
<P>
The Tribunal of Grand Instance of Nanterre ordered Le Pen to
pay compensations from one to 5,000 francs (0.17 to 830 U.S.
dollars) to 11 associations which charged him for damages
inflicted with his remarks.
</P>
<P>
Le Pen is also ordered to pay 300,000 francs (50,000 U.S.
dollars) to publish the court judgement in 10 national and
regional newspapers and six weeklies.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time for Le Pen to be condemned for saying
that the gas chambers in Nazi death camps were only "a detail."
He was condemned for similar declarations in 1991.
</P>
<P>
After the court made the verdict, Le Pen denounced it as "a
decision without foundation in law."
</P>
<P>
The condemnation was welcomed by the Union of Jewish Students
of France (UEJF), which said that it would continue to be vigilant
and intensify its fight against the remarks of Le Pen and his
party.
</P>
<P>
The Representative Council of Jewish Institutions of France
(CRIF) said that it would never compromise with Le Pen and the FN.
</P>
<P>
"The justice has just condemned once more Jean-Marie Le Pen
for having denied the tragic dimension of the Holocaust in a
provocative manner in Munich by the side of a former SS Waffen
Nazi," said the CRIF. 
</P>
</TEXT>
