<HEADLINE> DHA Reports on Flooding Situation in Peru </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 26 (xinhua) -- Heavy rains during
December have caused flooding and landslides in the northern,
central and southeastern parts of Peru, a release form the United
Nations Department of Humanitarian Affairs (DHA) said today.
</P>
<P>
In its situation report on Peru, the DHA said that a state of
emergency has been declared in the departments of Tumbes, Piura,
Lambayeque, La Libertad, Ancash, Arequipa, Moquwgua, Tacna, Puno,
Cajamarca, Cusco, Ayacucho, Apurimac and Huancavelica.
</P>
<P>
The departments of Tumbes and Pasco were reported to have been
the most hit by floods and landslides, affecting 4,786 people.
Some 24 kilometers of roads and eight bridges have been destroyed
there.
</P>
<P>
The floods and landslides have also affected agriculture, with
approximately 2,763 hectares of bananas and rice destroyed in
Tumbes and Pasco.
</P>
<P>
The destruction of roads and bridges has isolated several
districts in the northern and central regions of Peru.
</P>
<P>
The country's National Institute for Civil Defense estimated
that 9,279 people have been affected by the floods and landslides,
which have damaged some 1,390 houses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
