<HEADLINE> 11 Prisoners Escape Custody in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 26 (Xinhua) -- Eleven trial-awaiting
prisoners escaped from police custody this morning in Kokstad, a
city about 180 kilometers southwest of Durban, South African
Press Association (SAPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The men used a sharp instrument to dig a hole under their cell
and then fled, SAPA said.
</P>
<P>
Police noticed that the suspects, facing charges ranging from
rape to arson, were missing early this morning while doing
routine morning checks.
</P>
<P>
Today's escape was the second at the Kokstad police cells in
less than two months. Earlier, nine prisoners escaped from the
police holding cells through a hole.
</P>
<P>
Escapes are frequent in South African jails. In the 15 months
till March this year, more than 4,200 prisoners slipped from
their cells.
</P>
<P>
The nation was shocked when six of the most dangerous men in
the country escaped from a Pretoria prison at the beginning of
the month.
</P>
<P>
A large amount of escapes were blamed on corruption of warders
and activities of crime syndicates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
