<HEADLINE> Turkey Denies Violating Greek Airspace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 26 (Xinhua) -- Turkey today denied the Greek
claims that Turkish jets violated Greek airspace, describing the
accusation as "baseless."
</P>
<P>
A written statement of Turkish Foreign Ministry said that the
Turkish warplanes were flying in international airspace on
Thursday, but were intercepted by 10 Greek fighters.
</P>
<P>
"The jets were performing their routine habitual training
flights" and Turkey had always abided by the agreement between
the two countries, it said.
</P>
<P>
Greek Defense Ministry Thursday claimed that 12 Turkish F-16
jets violated Greek airspace, saying that Athens would not
tolerate such provocations.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Greece, both members of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization, have long been at odds over several issues,
including the limits of airspace, rights of sea-bed mineral
resources as well as the protracted Cyprus problem. 
</P>
