<HEADLINE> Cypriot FM Slams Turkish Cypriots' Decision of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot Foreign Minister
Ioannis Kasoulides has described a decision by the Turkish
Cypriot side to halt the U.N.-sponsored bicommunal talks as an
"extortionist move," a local newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, Taner Etkin, the "foreign minister" of the
self-styled Turkish Cypriot republic in northern Cyprus,
announced that the Turkish Cypriot side has decided to halt the
Cyprus bicommunal talks with the Greek Cypriot side, which is
aimed at reaching a settlement in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
He said the decision will give the Turkish Cypriot side to
study Luxembourg European Council decision, taken earlier this
month, to begin accession talks with Cyprus in spring of 1998.
</P>
<P>
After the European Union Luxembourg summit, Turkish Cypriot
leader Rauf Denktash announced that the bicommunal negotiations
are "dead," and said that he will no longer discuss the subject
with the United Nations and the Cypriot government.
</P>
<P>
Telling Greek language newspaper Delini (Afternoon), Kasoulides
said when the negotiations between the Greek Cypriots and Turkish
Cypriots start, everyone will undertake their responsibilities. "A
negative policy on the part of Ankara and Denktash will prove
damaging for them," he added.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated south
and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974, when Turkish
troops landed and took over the 37 percent of the island in the
wake of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. peace efforts to solve the Cyprus problem have so far
failed to achieve progress.
</P>
<P>
Two rounds of U.N.-sponsored direct talks held this summer
between Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides and Denktash ended in
failure, because Denktash refused to negotiate unless the EU
withholds its decision to start accession talks with Cypriot
government. 
</P>
