<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-27 15:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1998, Unique Opportunity to Settle Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 27 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. envoy to Cyprus today
said the U.N. believes 1998 offers a unique opportunity to settle
the Cyprus problem, but warned of negative consequences if this
opportunity is not seized.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Cyprus News Agency today, U.N. Resident
Representative in Cyprus Gustave Feissel said that "we are
approaching a defining moment after the February presidential
elections (in Cyprus) and 1998 will be a very important year."
</P>
<P>
But if peace talks, scheduled to begin in March 1998, end
inconclusively, as the two rounds of U.N.-led talks in last summer
did, the consequences would be much more serious, the U.N. envoy
noted.
</P>
<P>
Two rounds of direct talks held in July and August between
President Glafcos Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash ended in failure, because Denktash refused to negotiate
unless the European Union (EU) withholds its decision to start
accession talks with Cyprus in spring next year.
</P>
<P>
Conditions in next year, which would be better than that this
year, would induce everyone to become very focused on the Cyprus
problem, Feissel said.
</P>
<P>
The start of accession talks with the EU is one such condition,
he said, adding that this marks an important factor which should
impel everybody to display the necessary resolve to reach an
overall agreement.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus problem has remained unresolved since 1974 when the
island was divided after Turkish troops landed and took over the
northern third of the island in the wake of a failed pro-Athens
coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
The EU Luexembourg summit earlier this month decided to start
accession talks with the Cyprus Republic in next spring.
</P>
<P>
Feissel, however, refrained from commenting on Turkish views
that accession talks would signal the permanent division of the
island, but noting that neither Turkey nor the Turkish Cypriots
are happy with the EU decision.
</P>
<P>
"If we had significant progress in the Cyprus question, no
doubt their reaction would be very different," the top
U.N. official in Cyprus said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that perhaps the lack of political will would be
the most important hurdle in a settlement in Cyprus. But the
U.N. envoy expressed the hope that this situation would change,
because all parties concerned had realized it was in their
interests to work out a settlement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971227.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-27 </DATE_TIME>
