<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971227.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liaoning Restructures State-Owned Firms (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The province will encourage 130 prosperous state-owned
enterprises and enterprise groups to expand their scale of low
cost production by using capital, technology and the market as the
linkage.
</P>
<P>
Wen said that 160 medium-sized and large state-owned
enterprises will be merged to ensure that 30 billion yuan in idle
assets will be regrouped for effective use.
</P>
<P>
During the process of reform, between 250,000-300,000 redundant
workers will be laid-off by industrial firms in each of the next
three years, said Wen, adding that the figure will climb to
800,000 by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Proper arrangements for laid-off workers is a key to
maintaining rapid and sustained economic development. All
employment agencies and training centers must create more jobs and
offer better services, said Wen.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning, a leading industrial base built in the 1950s, once
produced 80 percent of the country's iron and steel and 60 percent
of heavy machinery. The province was the first to practice the
planned economy and the last to shift to the socialist market
economy.
</P>
<P>
The province has 926 medium- to large-sized state-owned
enterprises, or about 10 percent of the national total. The
concentration of said enterprises represented a major economic
powerhouse during the years of planned economy.
</P>
<P>
However, the said state-owned enterprises are now facing
unprecedented challenges in the wake of the socialist market
economy, with between 40-50 percent of Liaoning's enterprises
operating in the red. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971227.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liaoning Restructures State-Owned Firms (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Liaoning, one of China's
heavy industrial bases, will allow 90 percent of its medium-sized
and large state-owned enterprises merge with firms of different
ownerships over the next three years as part of a strategic
restructuring plan.
</P>
<P>
The province will transform a limited small number of large amd
medium-sized enterprises in the primary industrial sector, which
are considered vital to the national economy, into state-owned or
state holding firms, according to Liaoning Governor Wen Shizhen.
</P>
<P>
The program will in turn cultivate and fully support the
development of 60 competitive large industrial firms or enterprise
groups, said Wen, the former director of a large state-owned
enterprise.
</P>
<P>
The combined assets of the 60 firms will soar to 400 billion
yuan by the end of the century, with annual sales revenue expected
to hit 280 billion yuan. The ratio of their value-added output to
the total volume for the province will jump from 48 percent in
1996 to 60 percent by 2000.
</P>
<P>
Conditions permitting, profitable enterprises will have the
opportunity to raise funds by floating shares on the stock market
and to acquiring loss-making enterprises through share transferrals
and the acquisition of shares, creditor's and land rights, mergers
and the establishment of joint ventures and associations.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 200 small poorly managed lossing-making enterprises
would be allowed to transfer their assets through the property right
market in order to regain their vitality.
</P>
</TEXT>
