<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chengdu Battles River Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Today's completion of a
project to harness the Jinjiang River has benefited 100,000 people
in Chengdu, capital of southwest China's Sichuan Province.
</P>
<P>
The Jinjiang, which traverses the central part of the city,
formerly contributed to the fame and glamor of Chengdu's many
historic and cultural events.
</P>
<P>
However, since the 1950s, the level of pollution in the river
has grown dramatically due to falling water levels in the upper
reaches of the river and increasing discharges of waste from the
city, both of which have created major problems for some 100,000
poverty-stricken people living in the river valley. Some two
million residents living in the lower reaches of the river have
also suffered from the pollution.
</P>
<P>
Since 1993, the city government has invested 2.7 billion yuan
(300 million US dollars) to harness a 19-kilometer section of the
river.
</P>
<P>
A sewer system, and power, water and communications systems have
been completed for the project whose construction takes five
years, with a large number of poverty-stricken people moving into
new housing. The project also included the completion of two main
roads in the river valley.
</P>
<P>
Economists have praised the effort as a first-class project in
urban construction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
