<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Offshore Loans at 119 Bln Dollars in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Bank Indonesia, the central
bank, says that Indonesia's external loans, including commercial
papers, stood at 119 billion U.S. dollars in June this year and
not 200 billion dollars as put by some press reports.
</P>
<P>
Some 54 billion dollars of the amount belongs to government
loans and the rest private sector loans, Antara News Agency today
quoted Bank Indonesia Director Boediono as saying in a press
release.
</P>
<P>
Boediono said that as of September, the loans went down to 118
billion dollars, with 52.4 billion dollars in government loans and
65.6 billion in private sector loans.
</P>
<P>
He also said Bank Indonesia's record tallied with World Bank
reports.
</P>
<P>
Various domestic valuable papers held by foreigners, such as
Bank Indonesia certificates, bonds, promissory notes, commercial
papers, deposit certificates and medium-term notes, reached 21.2
billion dollars at the end of June and dropped to 15.3 billion
dollars at the September-end, he said.
</P>
<P>
These figures were obtained based on a survey of custodian
banks and have been synchronized with figures from the team of the
International Monetary Fund (IMF), he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
