<HEADLINE> WHO Acts to Tackle Cholera in E. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, December 27 (Xinhua) -- The World Health
Organization (WHO) has decided to set up a task force in Addis
Ababa to curb the spread of cholera in east African countries.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed here by Tadesse Molla, head of epidemiology
and AIDS department of the Ethiopian Ministry of Health, the
Ethiopian News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The task force to be established in the Ethiopian capital next
month, Tadesse said, will devise strategies through which the
spread of the disease could be curbed alongside the enhancement
of the storage and procurement of medicinal drugs.
</P>
<P>
The task force will review the experience of each country in
the region in preventing diarrhea and draw a three-year plan of
action before it set out to undertake its activities, he noted.
</P>
<P>
It also offers trainings to health professionals on how to
tackle the cholera epidemic in the region, Tadesse added.
</P>
<P>
According to the WHO announcement, an outbreak of cholera has
killed over 2,600 lives this year in east African countries. The
spread of the infectious disease had been aggravated by heavy
rain, poor sanitation and inadequate medicinal response in the
region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
