<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bonn Agrees to Compensate Holocaust Survivors in E. Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 27 (Xinhua) -- The German government has agreed
in principle to set up a special fund to compensate Holocaust
survivors living in eastern Europe, a local newspaper said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
According to the German Tageszeitung newspaper, the agreement
was reached by the German government and the Jewish negotiators.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the German government will make payments
to the fund three times a year. And the Jewish Claims Conference
will administer the fund and use the money to pay monthly pensions
to east European Holocaust survivors.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have also agreed that about 17,000 to 20,000
people are eligible for the pension payments, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The deal, which is expected to be finalized in mid-January,
came after months of deadlocked negotiations. The German
government had insisted on a one-time compensation instead of
making the payment on a regular basis.
</P>
<P>
Germany had paid about 100 billion German marks (55 billion
U.S. dollars) to Holocaust survivors in the West since 1949.
</P>
<P>
But those Jewish survivors living in eastern Europe and the
former Soviet Union had been excluded from the compensation
programs during the Cold War. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
