<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Third Largest Chemical Business Set Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, December 27 (Xinhua) -- The Huajin Chemical Industry
Group, China's third largest chemical industry company, was
established today in Shenyang, capital of northeast China's
Liaoning Province.
</P>
<P>
The group, which has total assets of over 10 billion yuan (1.2
billion US dollars), is located in a traditional industrial base
which is home to 10 percent of the country's state-owned medium-
to large-sized enterprises with total fixed assets of some 500
billion yuan (60 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Liaoning Governor Wen Shizhen called the establishment of the
company "a major step in the transformation and adjustment of the
traditional industrial base and in restructuring Liaoning's
state-owned assets."
</P>
<P>
The Huajin Group consists of four former chemical giants in the
province -- the Liaohe Chemical Fertilizer Plant, Jinxi Natural
Gas Chemical Industry Plant, Panjin Ethylene Plant and Jinxi
Chemical Industry Plant.
</P>
<P>
The group's combined sales income this year is expected to
surpass five billion yuan (600 million US dollars), according to
Huajin Chairman Fen Enliang.
</P>
<P>
He said the group plans to invest 14 billion yuan (1.7 billion
US dollars) between 1998-2007 to initiate a series of new
projects, including the respective increase of its annual ethylene
and PVC (polyvinyl chloride) output to 360,000 tons and 200,000
tons.
</P>
<P>
The group is expected to become China's largest production base
for caustic soda, PVC, and chemical fertilizers. Huajin's total
assets are expected to hit 20 billion yuan (2.4 billion US
dollars), with projected annual sales income set at 10 billion
yuan (1.2 billion US dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
