<HEADLINE> Iraq, Jordan Start Talks on Oil Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Iraq and Jordan started talks
on bilateral oil trade today, which would be focused on securing
Jordan's needs of crude oil next year and the implementation of
joint projects, the Iraqi News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Minister of Oil Amir Mohamed Rashid held talks on the
issue with visiting Jordanian Minister of Energy and Mineral
Resources Mohammed Saleh Hourani.
</P>
<P>
Rashid said during the talks that Iraq will adhere to the
bilateral agreement to satisfy Jordan's needs for crude oil and
oil products, the news agency quoted Rashid as saying.
</P>
<P>
Iraq is keen on carrying out several projects in the fields of
oil and natural gas and a joint oil refinery in Jordan's Red Sea
port city of Aqaba, Rashid said.
</P>
<P>
Hourani, who arrived in Baghdad Friday, expressed confidence
that the ongoing talks will achieve affirmative results.
</P>
<P>
The two countries will also promote cooperation in oil
prospection and exploitation and the exchange of expertise.
</P>
<P>
Under the bilateral oil agreement, which is expected to be
renewed, Iraq has provided Jordan with 840,000 barrels of oil this
year, a rise of 7 percent compared to that of 1996. 
</P>
