<DOCNO> XIE19971227.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liaoning Unveils Trans-Century Development Blueprint (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, December 27 (Xinhua) -- The gross domestic product
(GDP) for Liaoning Province, a leading industrial base in
northeast China, will grow by an annual rate of 10 percent over
the next five years, according to Liaoning Governor Wen Shizhen.
</P>
<P>
Projections call for Liaoning's GDP to range between 680-710
billion yuan by the year 2002, and climb even further to 890-970
billion yuan by 2005, said Wen.
</P>
<P>
The province's total import-export value will hit 23 billion
US dollars by 2002, and will rise to 30 billion US dollars by
2005. The export value for 2002 will stand at 13 billion US
dollars, with the figure rising to 17 billion US dollars in
2005. The import value for 2002 will hit 10 billion US dollars,
and will rise even further to 13 billion US dollars in 2005.
</P>
<P>
The provincial revenue will soar to 35.2 billion yuan in 2002
and hit 46.8 billion yuan in 2005, with the average annual
growth rate standing at 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
The proportion which scientific and technological achievements
play in economic development will jump from the current 42
percent to 52 percent in 2002, and even further to 56 percent in
2005.
</P>
<P>
The respective ratios of the value-added of the agricultural,
industrial and service trades will grow dramatically from 14.3
percent, 49.1 percent and 36.6 percent in 1997 to 9.5 percent,
48.5 percent and 42 percent in 2002.
</P>
<P>
The net annual income of urbanites will grow from 8,000 yuan
in 2002 to 10,000 yuan in 2005, with levels for rural residents
rising from 4,500 yuan to 6,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning's efforts to accomplish said objectives will face both
opportunities and grave challenges, said Wen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971227.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liaoning Unveils Trans-Century Development Blueprint (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Successful macroeconomic controls and increased overseas
investment channeled into industry will facilitate the
revitalization of Liaoning's traditional heavy industrial base.
</P>
<P>
However, 926 medium- to large-sized state-owned enterprises are
still technologically backward and mismanaged as a result of the
planned economy which was in place for some three decades.
</P>
<P>
The governor said the province will attempt to reverse the
passive situation by promoting successful state-owned enterprises,
establishing enterprise groups and allowing loss-making firms to
go bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning has listed the petrochemical, metallurgical,
electronics and information, and machinery industries as pillar
industries for the next five years, said Wen.
</P>
<P>
In terms of the electronics industry, priority will be placed
on the development of computers and software, as well as
on telecommunications and consumer electronics products and new
components.
</P>
<P>
The automobile manufacturing industry will place emphasis on
light-weight vans and bus production. Power generation equipment
manufacturers should strive for development of high-voltage
products.
</P>
<P>
Sixty-six percent of medium- to large-sized state-owned
enterprises, especially pillar industries, will establish joint
ventures or cooperative ties with overseas companies.
</P>
<P>
Local governments will allow state firms to either transfer
stock rights or sell operational rights in various forms.
</P>
<P>
Measures will be adopted to encourage foreign banks to open
branches in Liaoning in a bid to facilitate financial
cooperation between the province and other parts of the world,
according to Wen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
