<HEADLINE> Malaysia's State Govts Urged to Set up Disaster Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian National
Disaster Management and Relief Committee Chairman Mohamed Rahmat
Saturday urged state governments in the country to set up their
own disaster funds to ensure immediate aid to victims.
</P>
<P>
The local governments need to set up disaster funds of their
own because assistance from the Committee would take time due to
the procedures involved, he explained.
</P>
<P>
For instance, any financial aid exceeding 20,000 ringgit (more
than 5,000 U.S. dollars) requires the prior approval of the
cabinet, he said.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia comprises 13 states, as well as the capital city of
Kuala Lumpur and Labuan which form a Federal Territory.
</P>
<P>
At a function to provide aid from the National Disaster Relief
Fund to 18 families whose homes and properties were damaged in two
storms in July and August in the northern state of Perak, Mahamed
also urged the people to cooperate with the government in reducing
disasters caused by negligence like accidents in factories, the
Bernama news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He said the Fund had so far raised 2.2 million ringgit (about
570,000 U.S. dollars) although the target is 4 million ringgit.
</P>
<P>
Mohamed also asked the Science, Technology and Environment
Ministry to implement safety status regulations on factories as
quickly as possible to reduce accidents or disasters caused by
negligence.  
</P>
</TEXT>
