<HEADLINE> Somalis Slam Ethiopia's Position on Cairo Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Former Somali military
officers today condemned Ethiopia's move in denying the outcome
of the Cairo declaration by the Somali factions.
</P>
<P>
Colonel Ali Hashi Barale, spokesman for 250 former Somali
military officers has described Ethiopia's condemnation of the
Cairo agreement as "unfortunate on Ethiopia's part."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said today in south Mogadishu that Ethiopia has
noted that its diplomacy is still stuck on the previous
traditional hostility between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Colonel Barale, a former commandos officer who led a brigade
that participated in the 1977 Somali-Ethiopian war, has warned
Ethiopia against what he called its constant interruption in
Somalia's peace process.
</P>
<P>
"Let Ethiopia support this agreement if she wanted peace for
Somalia," he said.
</P>
<P>
Barale has advised Ethiopia to change its position in the
recent Cairo agreement and pull out its troops from Somalia's
territories, otherwise, he said, this move could have a negative
impact on the future relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
This statement by the Somali former army officers came after
the Ethiopian government condemned the Egyptian government for
what they called the hijacking of Somalia peace process by
hosting the recent Cairo meeting.
</P>
<P>
The position of Ethiopia has also created great anger in the
Somali communities who are now expecting peace after a seemingly
endless civil war.
</P>
<P>
"I think all Ethiopia meant is to take the credibility of
finding a solution to Somalia's long standing crises," said
Muhidin Hashi Nur, a businessman in Bakara market. "But they
failed in bringing all Somalia's sides to the negotiating table,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, faction leader Hussein Mohamed Aidid has expressed
concern over Ethiopia's stance in the Cairo meeting. However, he
said Ethiopia is independent to make its own evaluations on the
agreement in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
The Somali factions who signed the pact in Cairo are expected
to send a joint delegation to Ethiopia on Monday. The members of
the delegation include Ali Mahdi Mohamed, Osman Ali Atto and
representatives from Hussein Aidid's side, and they are planning
to meet with the Ethiopian prime minister in Addis Ababa on
Tuesday to brief him on how the meeting in Cairo went on and its
results. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
