<HEADLINE> Black Box of Crashed SilkAir Plane Found </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, December 27 (Xinhua) -- The Civil Aviation Authority
of Singapore (CAAS) and SilkAir confirmed on Saturday that the
flight data recorder, commonly known as the black box, of the
crashed SilkAir flight MI185 was found after nine days of search.
</P>
<P>
But the CAAS and SilkAir said they had no further information
to add to Indonesian Transport Minister Harianto Dahnutirto's
announcement that one of the two black boxes of the SilkAir flight
MI185 was found.
</P>
<P>
Divers from a search team recovered the flight data recorder at
the crash site Saturday morning. The team is still searching for
the cockpit voice recorder, the second black box.
</P>
<P>
Singapore Communications Minister Mah Bow Tan described the
finding as a "major discovery."
</P>
<P>
The SilkAir flight MI185 crashed at the Musi River, near
Palembang, Indonesia, on December 19, with 97 passengers and seven
crew members on board. No survivors were found from the crash.
</P>
<P>
The found black box will be taken to Washington's National
Transport Safety Bureau for tests and further investigations,
local press reports said.
</P>
<P>
Minister Mah cautioned people against high expectations, saying
that it would take three to five months to get to the bottom of
the investigation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
