<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Largest Opposition Disbanded </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Ichiro Ozawa, leader of Japan's
largest opposition New Frontier Party (NFP), announced Saturday the
disbanding of the party to pave the way for the establishment of two
new parties.
</P>
<P>
One party will be based on Komei, a Buddhist-backed political
group, while the other is expected to be formed by members loyal to
Ozawa.
</P>
<P>
Party sources said Ozawa's new party, to be launched around
January, will comprise about 100 Diet (parliament) members, 80
members of the House of Representatives (lower house) and 20 of the
House of Councillors (upper house).
</P>
<P>
The new party aims to eventually ally itself with conservative
members of the ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) when the time
comes for Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto to step down, the sources
said.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Ozawa proposed in a meeting with Tomio Fujii, leader
of the Komei Party, that 19 House of Councilors legislators close to
Komei leave the NFP to fight next summer's Upper House election on
their own.
</P>
<P>
The 19 NFP members formerly belonged to Komeito, one of eight
parties and one group that merged in December 1994 to form the NFP.
</P>
<P>
Komei, which groups Upper House members and local assembly members
formerly belonging to Komeito, unanimously decided at an executive
meeting Friday morning to accept Ozawa's proposal, Fujii said.
</P>
<P>
Fujii said his group plans to hold a meeting to change Komei into a
new party involving the 19 upper house members in late January or
early February.
</P>
<P>
The NFP has 126 members in the 500-seat lower house, of whom 45
members formerly belonged to Komeito.
</P>
<P>
The NFP was the biggest winner of seats by proportional
representation in the July 1995 upper house election, with strong
support from the Soka Gakkai, Japan's largest lay Buddhist group.
</P>
<P>
Since Ozawa became president of the NFP two years ago, the party
has constantly been rocked by internal strife arising from its
creation through the merger of divergent political groups.
</P>
<P>
The wrangling, as well as the sagging popularity of the party, has
resulted in a number of defections from the party, including those of
former Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa and Tsutomu Hata. 
</P>
</TEXT>
