<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Insurance Premiums Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 27 (Xinhua) -- After three years of falling
premium income, Hong Kong insurance business reversed the downturn
to achieve a 5.7 percent growth in the first nine months of the
year, according to a local insurance official.
</P>
<P>
Saturday's South China Morning Post quoted Insurance
Commissioner Alan Wong Chi-kong as saying that the rebound was
prompted by double-digit premium growth recorded in motor
insurance and employee compensation business.
</P>
<P>
In the first nine months, motor insurance achieved premium
growth of 12.7 percent compared with the same period of last year,
the first time motor insurance recorded growth after three
consecutive years of declining premiums.
</P>
<P>
Employee compensation insurance also recorded 14.5 percent
premium growth in the first nine months of the year -- the first
time this type of insurance has shown growth since 1994.
</P>
<P>
Mr. Wong expected general insurance growth would continue next
year in spite of a forecast economic adjustment for Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"The sale of public housing estates will increase the need for
fire insurance which will benefit the general insurance
companies," he said.
</P>
<P>
Life insurance premiums also enjoyed double-digit growth in the
first nine months, the commissioner revealed, adding that he
expected life insurance to carry the strong momentum into next
year as members of the public become more aware of the importance
of insurance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
