<HEADLINE> Russian Mountaineer Believed Dead in Himalaya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, December 27 (Xinhua) -- A Russian climber who
attempted the Annapurna I in the Himalayas on Christmas Day was
believed dead, said the Nepali Tourism Ministry on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Anatoly Boukreev, 39, was believed to be swept away on Thursday
by an avalanche while he was at 5,900 meters, the Nepali spokesman
quoted Italian climber Simone Moro as saying.
</P>
<P>
Moro was rescued on Friday from the mountain in west Nepal by a
helicopter.
</P>
<P>
"I shouted for 20 minutes and looked for him but did not find
his body," Moro, 30, said after being flown to Kathmandu.
</P>
<P>
Moro and Boukreev were attempting to scale the steep south face
of the 8,091-meter Annapurna I, the world's 10th highest mountain.
</P>
<P>
Boukreev was a noted mountaineer by scaling 11 of the world's
14 peaks over 8,000 meters, including the world's tallest peak of
Qomolangma three times.
</P>
<P>
Annapurna I was well known for its fatal avalanches which have
claimed 46 lives so far. 
</P>
