<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnamese Suffering From Poisonous Chemicals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of Vietnamese have
suffered from poisonous chemicals every year, the Vietnamese
newspaper "Lao Dong" Saturday quoted a report of the Ministry of
Health as saying.
</P>
<P>
Many people are regularly exposed to carcinogens and other
toxic substances, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The Plant Protection Department under the Ministry of
Agriculture and Rural Development said 2,500 to 3,000 tons of
insecticides, herbicides and pesticides are used across the
country every year.
</P>
<P>
Some insecticides, such as methaphos monitor, azodrin, and
methyl parathion are still used in Vietnam, even though they are
banned by the World Health Organization.
</P>
<P>
Smuggled and illegally manufactured chemicals also add to the
problem, with some 30 companies, 20 factories and nearly 100
foreign firms manufacturing the products.
</P>
<P>
Although the Health Ministry has issued a list of chemicals
barred from food processing, the illegal use of chemicals in food
is still rampant.
</P>
<P>
This has led to a high chemical-related mortality rate,
following major killers like tuberculosis, lung cancer and traffic
accidents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971227.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Financial Crisis Not Likely to Occur in China, Says Top Banker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Chinese top banker Dai
Xianglong said here today that financial crisis that has hit some
of Southeast Asian countries will not likely occur in China. But
the risks hidden in the country's financial sector cannot be
overlooked.
</P>
<P>
Reporting to the National People's Congress (NPC) Standing
Committee at its 29th session here today, Dai said the lessons to
draw from recent financial crisis in some Asian nations include
avoiding a "bubble economy", and maintaining a sound financial
system, a reasonable monetary system and an adequate foreign
exchange reserve.
</P>
<P>
"It is also very important to open financial sectors in a very
prudent and step-by-step way," said Dai, governor of the People's
Bank of China (PBC), or the central bank.
</P>
<P>
He noted that a financial crisis in some Asian countries will
not possibly occur in China as its overall economic development is
healthy and financial situation fairly stable.
</P>
<P>
China's foreign exchange reserve will exceed 140 billion US
dollars by the end of this year and its currency Renminbi remains
stable. By the end of June this year, China attracted 316.5
billion US dollars in foreign capital. Of the total, 197.9 billion
US dollars are direct foreign investment and 118.6 billion are
foreign debt.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the country's foreign debt payment rate and debt
ratio stand at 11.81 percent and 13.97 percent, respectively,
lower than the international standard risk lines.
</P>
<P>
"Nevertheless, we should not overlook the problems existing in
our financial sector," cautioned the central bank governor, citing
the high rate of bad loans in the state commercial banks as a
major risk.
</P>
<P>
The very small number of non-banking financial institutions are
operating poorly, and a few of them even have payment problems.
</P>
<P>
To draw money from general public and enterprises, some
central department and government at local levels grant
permissions for setting up quasi-financial institutions which do
not have financial expertises and are not under strict financial
supervision.
</P>
<P>
Other problems, Dai added, include irregularities in stock and
futures markets.
</P>
<P>
"If not promptly addressed, these problems might seriously
undermine our credit and banking system, hamper with the national
economy and social stability," he said.
</P>
<P>
Dai pledged that the central bank should continue conducting
in-depth financial reform, strengthening its supervision and law
enforcement in the coming 1998 and carrying out a nationwide
inspection in this regard. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971227.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-27 10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudi Bank Helps Support Lebanese Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia's largest bank
the National Commercial Bank has lent more than 600 million U.S.
dollars to the Lebanese central bank to help it prop up the
Lebanese pound, local Beirut Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
The move follows speculations that the Lebanese government will
devalue the Lebanese pound under the current difficult economic
situation, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
According to bank sources, due to the bank loan, the Lebanese
currency has been strengthened from 1,531 pounds to one dollar to
1,523 pounds.
</P>
<P>
The three-year low-interest loan granted on December 24 will
increase the foreign reserves of Lebanon's central bank to about
6.4 billion dollars, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon's central bank has spent 2 billion dollars this year to
support the pound.
</P>
<P>
The report of the Beirut Times said the move will enable the
Lebanese central bank to lower the interest rates in the near
future, and help the government pay back part of the public debt
which stands at about 13 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
