<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Faces Increasing Water Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Wang Bingqian, vice-chairman
of the Standing Committee of the National People's Congress, said
here today that China faces worsening water problems in his report
to the on-going session of the NPC Standing Committee.
</P>
<P>
Based on the result of inspections over the implementation of
the Water Law, Wang said: "The chances are growing that China
might suffer a possible severe water shortage in the first half of
the 21st century, and the reality will be stark for our nation."
</P>
<P>
According to Wang, groups of NPC Standing Committee members
made inspection tours of Heilongjiang, Henan and Hunan provinces
from September to October.
</P>
<P>
They found most flood-control projects in these provinces
inadequate and these projects will hardly be capable of resisting
big floods.
</P>
<P>
In some areas, large-scale development and construction
projects have either narrowed or blocked the waterway. In
additon, the situation is worsening by land reclamation projects
and soil erosion.
</P>
<P>
Wang went on to say that the gap in water demand and supply
will become even more acute along with the expansion of national
economy and population.
</P>
<P>
"China is estimated to possibly reach its extreme in the
development of its water resource by the year 2030 when its
population reaches 1.6 billion," he said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Wang noted, soil erosion and water pollution are
"appalling". About 3.6 million sq km of land, or 38 percent of the
country's total, are suffering from soil erosion and the figure is
rising at an average annual increase of 10,000 sq km, he added.
</P>
<P>
Half of the waterways in China's seven water systems have been
polluted to varying extent and one tenth of the water in these
areas is no longer usable.
</P>
<P>
"The situation cannot be resolved in the near future," Wang
said.
</P>
<P>
He called for still closer attention to the problems and prompt
action to address the situation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
