<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profile: Ex V-P Runs for Kenya's Presidency Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Mwai Kibaki, former Kenyan
Vice President and Chairman of the opposition Democratic Party
(DP), is seen as the most serious challenger to incumbent
President Daniel arap Moi in Monday's elections.
</P>
<P>
His popularity has risen from 13.7 percent in the first poll
at the end of November to 20.8 percent in the second after two
weeks of campaign and four days before the voting, second only to
Moi with 40.8 percent in the first poll and 40.2 in the second.
</P>
<P>
In his manifesto, Kibaki says he can transform Kenya into a
land of plenty and free from corruption, creating half a million
jobs every year by emphasising labor-intensive projects.
</P>
<P>
"I see a Kenya with enough to eat and spare, I see a land of
plenty, free from corruption. I promise a government that listens
to Kenyans and responds," said Kibaki.
</P>
<P>
A DP government will treat shelter as a basic human right, he
claimed, adding that his government shall set the ceiling for
mortgage interest rates at 10 percent for rural housing and 15
percent for inexpensive urban houses.
</P>
<P>
In the few months leading to the poll this year, his party has
suffered a number of telling defections, prominent among them is
the departure of Charity Ngilu, who now is also a serious rival
in the race.
</P>
<P>
The 66-year-old Kibaki "has been variously described as a
scholar, technocrat, and one of the most brilliant minds in
Africa," the independent East African Standard newspaper
commented.
</P>
<P>
A member of Kikuyu, the largest tribe making up about 25
percent of Kenya's population, Kibaki is expected to do well in
Central Province.
</P>
<P>
Born in Othaya, Nyeri District, Central Kenya in 1931, little
Kibaki herded goats and cattle like most African children,
although his father, by local standards, was a wealthy man who
made his fortune originally by selling tobacco snuff.
</P>
<P>
The father had two wives with the second borne him five
children, Kibaki being the fourth.
</P>
<P>
Kibaki went to Gatuyaine Village School in 1940 from which he
proceeded to board Karima Mission School, then the prestigious
Mangu High School in Thika, before attending Makerere University,
in Kampala, Uganda in 1951 for a BA course in economics, history
and political science.
</P>
<P>
He thereafter enrolled at the London School of Economics in
1956 for a B. Sc. in public finance before returning to Makerere
as an economic lecturer.
</P>
<P>
Kibaki got involved in politics in 1960 as the National
Executive Officer of the Kenya African National Union (KANU) and
became a member of parliament since the country's independence
from Britain in 1963.
</P>
<P>
He was appointed Assistant Minister for Economic Planning and
Development the following year, and later promoted to Minister
for Commerce and Industry until 1969 when he switched to the
Finance and Planning portfolio.
</P>
<P>
During his tenure as Minister for Finance and Planning between
1969-1978, he was constantly accused of employing in his ministry
people from his Kikuyu tribe and in particular residents of
Othaya Constituency which is his home town.
</P>
<P>
When Moi took over from late President Jomo Kenyatta, Kibaki
was elevated as the fourth vice president in independent Kenya in
October, 1978. He had served the post for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
In March 1988, Moi dismissed him from the vice presidency and
demoted him to Health Minister reportedly due to their disputes
over style, minor issues and personality differences.
</P>
<P>
At the time, Kibaki had just won Othaya parliamentary seat for
the third consecutive time.
</P>
<P>
In December 1991, he resigned from the government and in
January 1992 founded the DP. He stood against Moi in the first
democratic multi-party elections in December 1992 but only came
third in the poll after Moi and Kenneth Matiba, winning 19.45
percent of the vote -- a total of 1,035,507 votes.
</P>
<P>
Kibaki is a Christian and the father of three children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971227.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NPC Vice-Chairman on Implementation of Agriculture Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 27 (Xinhua) -- A senior legislator today
called for more input in agriculture, an improved grain
circulation system, faster spread of agro-techniques, alleviated
burden on farmers, and appropriate use of poverty-relief funds.
</P>
<P>
At a plenary meeting of the ongoing 29th session of the
National People's Congress (NPC) Standing Committee this morning,
Buhe, vice-chairman of the NPC Standing Committee, made the appeal
in his report on inspecting the implementation of Agriculture Law.
</P>
<P>
In October this year, the NPC Standing Committee dispatched
three inspection teams to look into the law's implementation in
the Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region, and Guizhou and Jiangxi
provinces.
</P>
<P>
That was the fourth time the NPC Standing Committee sent
inspection teams to look into the law's implementation.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the standing committees of the provincial
people's congresses in Guangdong, Gansu, Hunan and Liaoning
provinces were asked to make investigations in this regard in
their respective areas.
</P>
<P>
Buhe said both the central and local governments have increased
input in the agricultural sector and helped ease the farmers's
burden and improve the grain circulation system despite the
country's relatively-tight monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted, there still exist some problems which
"should not be neglected but be resolved in the future work."
</P>
<P>
This year China scored a third consecutive good grain harvest,
which resulted in abundant farm produce and help push the national
economy forward. But there are some new problems that have cropped
up in the post-harvest period, Buhe said.
</P>
<P>
In this sense, he added, a grain circulation system to comply
with the socialist market economy and macro-control of the central
government have to be introduced.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he urged local governments to take effective measures
to publicize advanced agricultural techniques.
</P>
<P>
With regard to farmers' burden, Buhe noted that the farmers in
some areas are still subjected to illegal fund-raising, random fee
collection and fining. Therefore, he called on local governments
to further increase management and to earnestly safeguard the
farmers' legitimate interests. 
</P>
</TEXT>
