percent of the votes garnered all over the country.
</P>
<P>
The poll conducted by the universities research team in the
past one week shows that Moi would get more than 25 percent of
the votes in seven of the country's eight provinces.
</P>
<P>
Under Kenya's Constitution, the winning presidential candidate
must garner at least 25 percent of the votes cast in at least
five of Kenya's eight provinces.
</P>
<P>
According to the poll, Mwai Kibaki of the Democratic Party of
Kenya was in the second place with 16.2 percent of votes,
followed by Ford-Kenya's Wamalwa Kijana (12.7 percent), Raila
Odinga of the National Development Party (10.0 percent) and
Charity Ngilu of the Social Democratic party (9.3 percent).
</P>
<P>
The provinces in which Moi is to get more than 25 percent
votes are Rift Valley (65.98), Western (40.12), Coast (67.58),
Eastern (37.36), Nairobi (34.16), Northeastern (49.57) and Nyanza
(38.31).
</P>
<P>
The results released Friday show that 14 opposition
presidential candidates have their support among the youth,
educated and urban-based voters while Moi draws solid support
from the old and rural voters where the Opposition has not
penetrated. 
