<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Malaysia's CPO, Tin &AMP; Rubber Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's markets of
crude palm oil (CPO) physicals, tin and rubber closed the week all
higher.
</P>
<P>
The CPO physicals market strengthened this week on bullish
export figures released by Societe Generale de Surveillance (M)
Sdn Bhd for December 1-25, which stood at 572,244 tons against
543,315 tons last month.
</P>
<P>
News that Indonesia would ban its January exports also
triggered short covering and gave additional support.
</P>
<P>
On the local market, December South was traded at 2,050 ringgit
(529.7 U.S. dollars) per ton from 1,970 ringgit (509 U.S. dollars)
per ton last week.
</P>
<P>
The Kuala Lumpur Tin Market (KLTM) throughout the
trading-shortened week this week was see-sawed in tandem with the
ringgit's volatility in the foreign exchange market.
</P>
<P>
The price on the KLTM, which was closed on Thursday for
Christmas, was one sen steadier at the week's close at 20.10
ringgit (5.19 U.S. dollars) per kg compared with 20.09 ringgit per
kg last week.
</P>
<P>
The week's turnover narrowed to 249 tons from 297 tons last
week.
</P>
<P>
This week, the Malaysian rubber market strengthened as players
were cautious on technical adjustments and in line with the
steadier regional markets.
</P>
<P>
January RSS One rose eight sen to 276.50 sen (71 U.S. cents)
per kg from 268.5 sen (69 U.S. cents) per kg last week while SMR
20 gained six sen to 272 sen (70 U.S. cents) per kg from last
week's 266 sen (68 U.S. cents) per kg.  
</P>
