<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kaunda Should Be Either Put on Trial or Released: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 27 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government
should either bring detained former president Kenneth Kaunda to
trial or to release him forthwith, South African President Nelson
Mandela's office said.
</P>
<P>
Presidential aide Jakes Gerwel said in a statement issued on
Friday night that the South African government noted with
disappointment and grave concern the arrest and detention in
Lusaka of Kaunda.
</P>
<P>
"We do trust that the matter of the detention of Dr. Kaunda
will be resolved speedily and in the interest of political
stability and good governance in Zambia and in our region," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Gerwel said Kaunda's detention, whatever the substantive
issues at stake, violated the commitment of the members of the
Southern African Development Community (SADC) to the promotion
and maintenance of democracy, good governance and human rights
within the region.
</P>
<P>
Zambia is a member state of the SADC.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda, 73, who led Zambia to independence in 1964, was on
Christmas detained under a state of emergency by paramilitary
police.
</P>
<P>
He was ordered detained for 28 days under provisions of the
state of emergency that followed a failed coup attempt on October
28 against his successor as president, Frederick Chiluba.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda appeared in court on Friday, but the judge refused to
release or charge him with his detention on Christmas Day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
