<HEADLINE> Deputy Chief of PLA General Staff on International Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Some unstable and uncertain
factors still exist in the political, economic and military sphere
in spite of the relative peace, stability and development that are
expected to be generally maintained in the international strategic
situation.
</P>
<P>
Xiong Guangkai, deputy chief of the general staff of the
Chinese People's Liberation Army (PLA), today made the remarks at
the 1997 annual meeting of the China Institute for International
Strategic Studies (CIISS), with an attendance of more than 100
people, retired army generals, veteran diplomats and scholars on
international issues.
</P>
<P>
Xiong, also president of CIISS, said the current international
situation is undergoing the most profound changes and adjustments
since the end of the Cold War. China is facing with both
opportunities and challenges, but the opportunities outweigh the
challenges, he added.
</P>
<P>
In view of a trend toward the world's strategic
multi-polarization, economic globalization and localization of
armed conflicts, Xiong said: "We should be vigilant in times of
safety, seize the opportunities and face up to the challenges, and
work along with the people of all nations to bring an even more
peaceful, stable and prosperous world into the next century."
</P>
<P>
Established in 1979, the CIISS has now forged academic ties
with more than 130 institutions in over 40 countries worldwide.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971227.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Electoral Campaign to End Tomorrow in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Electoral Commission
has announced that electoral campaign by all political parties
for the December 29 general elections would end Sunday, or on
December 28, Kenya Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
The daily newspaper quoted Samuel Kivuitu, chairman of the
commission, as saying Friday that campaigns would not be allowed
on Monday although candidates can make visits to polling stations
to check the process of the exercise.
</P>
<P>
He announced that all the balloting papers printed in Britain
had arrived in the country and the ballot boxes would be
displayed fully to voters on the polling day at all polling
stations.
</P>
<P>
The serial numbers of the ballot boxes will be printed in full
and will be displayed to voters at each station to avoid
confusion, the chairman added.
</P>
<P>
Kivuitu noted that the commission had directed returning
officers to ensure that lamp will be lit throughout the counting
exercise whether there will be electricity or not.
</P>
<P>
In order to guard against throwing away of some candidates'
votes, he said, the lamp will be lit from six o'clock in the
evening till morning even if the electricity or generator will be
on.
</P>
<P>
The Electoral Commission has released guidelines and
regulations for all election officials, candidates, poll agents
and persons taking part in the forthcoming general elections.
</P>
</TEXT>
