<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Kuala Lumpur Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 27 (Xinhua) -- The Kuala Lumpur Stock
Exchange (KLSE) market continued its downward plunge this week
with the benchmark Composite Index ending 27.8 points lower to
close at 560.96.
</P>
<P>
During the week, the all main board shares Emas Index dropped
7.19 points to 144.02 and the Industrial Index fell 7.22 points
to 1,091.66.
</P>
<P>
Total turnover fell to 556.945 million shares valued at 1.142
billion ringgit (295.09 million U.S. dollars) from 921.791 million
stocks worth 2.223 billion ringgit (574.41 million U.S. dollars)
last week.
</P>
<P>
The main board volume dwindled to 492.832 million stocks worth
1.023 billion ringgit (264.34 million U.S. dollars) from 831.514
million shares valued at 1.985 billion ringgit (512.91 million
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The second board volume declined to 64.114 million shares
valued at 119.083 million ringgit (30.77 million U.S. dollars)
from 90.276 million stocks worth 237.776 million ringgit (61.44
million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Off-market deals increased to 83.100 million stocks worth
498.437 million ringgit (128.79 million U.S. dollars) from 75.779
million shares valued at 290.246 million ringgit (74.99 million
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
One counter -- Patimas Computers Bhd -- opened its first
trading day on the second board on Tuesday at 2.50 ringgit, a 0.3
ringgit discount from its offer price of 2.80 ringgit, and it
ended the week at 2.47 ringgit.
</P>
<P>
This week, consumer product accounted 33.929 million shares
traded, industrial product 53.844 million shares, construction
32.232 million shares, trading/services 98.594 million shares,
infrastructure 5.623 million shares, finance 91.200 million
shares, hotels 4.331 million shares, properties 85.386 million
shares, plantations 24.406 million shares, mining 3.164 million
shares, trusts 1.273 million shares, closed-end fund 1.093 million
shares, loan stocks 25.354 million shares and transferable
subscription rights/warrants 32.403 million shares.
</P>
<P>
According to dealers, share prices on the KLSE are expected to
rebound next week on a mini rally ahead of the new year because
continued local fund support and persistent talk of more mergers
of local financial institutions would result in improved prices.
</P>
<P>
But if a rally does occur, it is expected to be a short-lived
one as the continued negative effects of uncertainty still
prevailed, they said, adding the benchmark CI is expected to test
the 600 level again, but resistance is expected at the 580 points
level. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
