<HEADLINE> Pakistani FM Explains Foreign Policy of His Country </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Foreign Minister
Gohar Ayub Khan said here Saturday the foreign policy of his
country is aimed at protecting its national interests as well as
promoting political stability and economic cooperation in the
region .
</P>
<P>
In his inaugural address at the Conference of Pakistan's South
Asia Envoys, Gohar underlined the imperatives of a rationally
formulated open foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
He said that in the backdrop of "hegemony which is still
sought" and the continuation of tensions, Pakistan desires
cooperative relations with all countries for the common benefits
of all peoples.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan has to steer a course which fundamentally protects
our national interests as well as promotes rapprochement,
political stability and economic cooperation in South Asia," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He regretted that the region remains mired in mutual suspicions
and distrust and old disputes and resultant tensions continue.
</P>
<P>
"Kashmir remains a major flash-point, large defense
establishments continue to burden our economies, new and more
sophisticated weapon systems are being inducted in our
neighborhood," he said.
</P>
<P>
Disarmament proposals and confidence building measures have
received dismissive responses, he said.
</P>
<P>
"It (Kashmir) continues to bedevil relations between Pakistan
and India, it is the primary reason for instability in South
Asia," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Minister pointed out that under the leadership of
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif, Pakistan has deliberately chosen the
path of dialogue.
</P>
<P>
"Ours is not a single-point agenda with India, we are prepared
to address all outstanding issues between the two countries in a
meaningful and an integrated manner," he said.
</P>
<P>
He believed that resolution of differences between Pakistan and
India, particularly the core issue of Jammu and Kashmir, will
usher in a new era of cooperation and mutually beneficial
interaction in South Asia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
