<HEADLINE> Iranian President to Start First Foreign Trip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami is scheduled to leave here for Turkmenistan Sunday for his
first foreign trip since he assumed office last August, local
daily Iran News reported today.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Khatami will attend the ground-breaking
ceremony of a pipeline for exporting natural gas of the Central
Asian country, the daily said.
</P>
<P>
The pipeline dubbed by Iranian media as a "peace pipeline" is
designed to supply regional and European countries with the
cheapest and cleanest energy based on a long-term contract.
</P>
<P>
The daily said that the pipeline will help promote multilateral
cooperation to guarantee the development, peace and prosperity of
the whole region.
</P>
<P>
Last May, the presidents of Iran, Turkmenistan and Turkey
agreed to build a 3,000 kilometers gas pipeline from Turkmenistan
to Turkey via Iran, which is estimated to cost 1.5 to 2.5 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Under the deal, Turkmenistan will supply 28-30 billion cubic
meters of natural gas annually to Turkey for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
Turkmenistan also intends to extend its gas export to European
countries through the pipeline. 
</P>
</TEXT>
