<HEADLINE> Shell's Distillate Synthesis Plant in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Shell's middle distillate
synthesis (MDS) plant in Bintulu, Malaysia, has been temporarily
closed down following an explosion on Thursday night, pending an
investigation, local report said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
With the closure of the 2.5 billion ringgit plant, which
produces an average of 400,000 tons of products such as middle
distillates, solvents, paraffins and waxes by conversion from
natural gas, all the 336 workers of Shell MDS have been told to
stay home until further notice, according to reports from Bintulu.
</P>
<P>
Shell Public Affairs head Saperi Rambli was quoted as saying
Saturday the plant had been shut down for safety and security
reasons as well as for damage control and assessment.
</P>
<P>
The plant located in East Malaysia's Sarawak state got fire
when its two tanks each filled with naphtha and kerosene exploded
at about 10:50 PM Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
The fire was put out Friday afternoon by about 150 firemen who,
according to the reports, are still on stand-by at the site of the
explosion to watch out for any untoward incident.
</P>
<P>
The explosion at the plant caused injuries to 12 people, of
whom, two injured employees of the plant are still warded at the
Bintulu Hospital for a broken wrist and head wounds respectively.
Ten others who were also injured in the mishap were given
outpatient treatment.
</P>
<P>
The plant's public affairs officer said that investigations
would be carried once the plant had been declared safe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
