<HEADLINE> Strike of Airline Pilots Banned in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Labor Secretary
Leonardo Quisumbing has ordered the ban of any strike or lockout
of Philippine Airlines pilots to prevent a disruption of services
especially during the holidays.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by Philippine Airlines said Saturday that
pilots who defy the order by participating in any illegal protest
action will automatically lose their employment status with the
airlines.
</P>
<P>
In his jurisdiction over the labor dispute between the airlines
and the Air Line Pilots Association of the Philippines assumed on
December 23, Quisumbing cited Philippine Airlines' indispensable
role to the national interest and that any work stoppage would
damage the economy.
</P>
<P>
"A strike at petitioner's work premises will undoubtedly
aggravate the financial woes of the petitioner which is still
reeling under the effects of heavy losses in the past few years,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Any strike or lockout might "choke the country's flag carrier
to death", not to mention its effect on the 14,000 employees and
their dependents and its grave and serious implications on the
national economy and the airline industry in particular, he added.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Airlines' pilots have staged several strikes in the
past two years for wage hike and other reasons, sometime seriously
disrupting the airline's services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
