<HEADLINE> Nepali Govt to Educate Youngsters on AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, December 27 (Xinhua) -- The Nepali government has
issued a six-point commitments paper on providing AIDS and
sexually transmitted disease (STD) prevention education to boys
and girls in and out of school, local newspapers reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The commitment paper, issued jointly by the Ministries of
Health and Women and Social Welfare, aims to increase the
participation of boys and girls in the prevention and control of
AIDS and STD by fostering a strong partnership among
policy-makers, community, teachers, parents and students, the
newspapers said.
</P>
<P>
The paper also encourages greater participation of boys and
girls in the design and implementation of the prevention programs,
the newspapers added.
</P>
<P>
Increasing access to quality and non-discriminatory AIDS/STD
services which are friendly towards boys and girls, and equal
rights among boys and girls are sought as well, the newspapers
said.
</P>
<P>
Education Minister K.B. Gurung has said that textbooks for
grades 6 and 7 contain education materials on AIDS and STD, and in
the near future grade 8 will also have such materials.
</P>
<P>
A total of 91 Nepalese have died of AIDS this year by the end
of November, according to the statistics issued recently.
</P>
</TEXT>
