<HEADLINE> Farmers Earn More Despite Natural Adversities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Farmers' per-capita income in
east China's Shandong Province increased by more than 300 yuan
this year despite adverse weather conditions.
</P>
<P>
In late summer and early autumn the province suffered one of
the worst droughts in 80 years and a windstorm. Approximately five
million hectares of crops were affected, leading to losses of 3.3
billion kilograms.
</P>
<P>
However, diversified economic activities advocated by the
provincial government helped farmers make up for their losses.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, by growing fruits and vegetables instead staples such
as wheat and rice, farmers increased their income by more than 100
yuan. Animal husbandry contributed approximately the same amount.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, efforts to industrialize agriculture also provided
opportunities for farmers to earn extra money. The province has
established 25,000 agriculture-related businesses, which increased
more than 20 billion yuan (2.4 billion US dollars) in economic
returns. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
