<HEADLINE> Fujian Province Capital Makes Gains in Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Fuzhou City, capital of east
China's Fujian Province, expects to put to use 1.25 billion
U.S. dollars in overseas funds and receive 2.01 billion
U.S. dollars in exports this year.
</P>
<P>
That would represent a rise of 11.6 percent in overseas funding
and 13 percent in exports over 1996.
</P>
<P>
The city, hometown of many overseas Chinese, now boasts 5,100
overseas-funded enterprises involving a total contractual
investment of over 13 billion U.S. dollars. The industrial output
of the enterprises in operation accounts for more than 60 percent
of the city's total.
</P>
<P>
Due to marked improvement in the investment environment, the
city has attracted dozens of overseas-funded companies with
investments of 30 million U.S. dollars each or more.
</P>
<P>
The overseas-funded companies are mainly in the fields of
electronics, machine-building, textiles, chemicals, building
materials and aquatic products.
</P>
<P>
The city has been turned into the country's largest center for
producing monitors, and turning out devices and automotive glass
products.
</P>
<P>
Local statistics show that the city will approve 430
overseas-funded projects this year, up 5 percent from last year,
involving 1.18 billion U.S. dollars of contractual investment, up
6.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The sales of joint ventures, cooperative enterprises and solely
foreign-funded companies are expected to top 30 billion yuan (3.75
billion U.S. dollars) this year, more than 18 percent more than
1996.
</P>
<P>
Last year these overseas-funded companies received 1.51 billion
U.S. dollars in exports, or 85 percent of the city's total,
according to local statistics.  
</P>
</TEXT>
