<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, December 27 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. citizen wanted for the
alleged murder of five people in the United States has been
arrested in Vietnam as part of an Intepol investigation.
</P>
<P>
Nguyen Thanh Thang, a 32-year-old American with Vietnamese
origin, was detained on December 22 by Vietnam's investigation
department, said a report in the Vietnam News Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Prior to his arrest at the Bac Lieu Township in the southern
province of Bac Lieu, Thang had been on the U.S. Federal Bureau of
Investigation's (FBI) list of 10 most-wanted criminals.
</P>
<P>
Born in the southern province of Soc Trang, Thang immigrated to
the United States in 1984, where he worked as a cook for Nhung, a
Vietnamese resident living in New York, until he was fired.
</P>
<P>
Thang, together with another U.S. citizen named Thrlomi Ther,
allegedly broke into Nhung's house and murdered Nhung and her
husband and fled to Canada and then to Vietnam in June 1992.
</P>
<P>
The FBI informed Vietnam's police about the case last August
via Interpol's Vietnam Office. 
</P>
