<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Increases Fund for Food Scheme </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Deputy Prime
Minister Anwar Ibrahim announced Saturday an additional government
allocation for the Fund for Food Scheme as part of the
government's efforts to promote and finance new investments in the
food sector to increase domestic food production.
</P>
<P>
after a meeting with local food producers here, Anwar, who is
also Finance Minister, told reporters that the increment of 100
million ringgit (about 3.87 ringgit is equal to one U.S. dollar)
for the Fund for Food Scheme, bringing the total to 700 million
ringgit, was also to contain inflationary pressures, prevent the
erosion of real incomes and reduce the import bill on food to
conserve foreign exchange earnings.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said the operational guidelines of the Fund, introduced
in 1993, which provides a minimum borrowing of 50,000 ringgit and
a maximum of three million ringgit per project at an interest rate
of 4 percent per annum to Malaysian-owned companies and
individuals, would remain unchanged and would continue to be
administered by the State Bank.
</P>
<P>
The finance minister said that the decision to expand the Fund
was to tackle the inadequate supply of food from domestic sources
which would contribute to domestic price pressures and increase
the already large food import bill.
</P>
<P>
During the first 10 months of the year, Malaysia imported food
worth 7.9 billion ringgit. According to Anwar, the bill is likely
to increase to 10 billion ringgit or 10 percent higher than last
year's total of 9.0 billion ringgit.
</P>
<P>
Food consumption accounts for slightly more than a third of
Malaysia's average household expenditure, Anwar said, adding that
increases in food prices contributed 56 percent of the increase in
the Consumer Price Index (CPI) during the first 11 months of the
year.
</P>
<P>
Financing under the scheme will be used for primary food
production, including aquaculture, animal husbandry, vegetable and
fruit farming as well as production of related food products,
mainly processed food for which the raw food materials must be
obtained from domestic sources and for local consumption.
</P>
<P>
The Fund can also be used to finance projects that will lead to
more efficient distribution of food and food products.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1,023 applications involving a sum of 301.3 million
ringgit have been approved since the Fund was introduced in 1993.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
