<HEADLINE> More Jobs Created by Foreign Projects in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 27 (Xinhua) -- More than 21,000 new jobs are
expected to be created this year in 363 foreign investment
projects valued at over eight billion Zimbabwe Dollars (about 600
million U.S. Dollars) approved by the Zimbabwe Investment Center.
</P>
<P>
According to the center's latest foreign investment
information for January to November of this year, 363 foreign
investment projects are expected to create 21,401 jobs in seven
sectors of the economy.
</P>
<P>
The positive response by the investors from various countries
in Europe, the United States, Africa, Asia and the Middle East,
was a result of the government's massive campaign to market the
country as the best investment place in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The projects approved range from manufacturing to tourism. Of
the 363 projects approved, over 303 were joint ventures between
foreign investors and local business people, in line with the
government's policy which encourages such ventures to ensure that
the local business people acquire skills to enable them to run
the companies when the foreign investors pull out.
</P>
<P>
The other 60 were direct foreign investments involving no
local partners.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. accounted for a bigger percentage of the total
investment value, while Britain ranked the second. 
</P>
</TEXT>
