<HEADLINE> Thailand Relaxes Material Imports for Feed Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 27 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government has agreed
to relax its policy on imports of maize, soybean meal and fishmeal
which are used as raw materials in the local animal feed industry
to help reduce its production cost.
</P>
<P>
The Thai cabinet earlier this week lifted the import quota
limits for soybean meal and fishmeal for 1998, according to the
Thai Animal Feed Producers Association.
</P>
<P>
But the government set a quota of 300,000 tons for maize
imports which will be allowed between March 1 and June 30 next
year, the association said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Also, the government will maintain low tariffs on the imports
and allow the imports on conditions that the prices of these
products on the domestic market will not fall below a certain
level.
</P>
<P>
The duty on soybean meal for 1998 will be reduced to five
percent from 10 percent beginning on January 1 next year. Yet if
the soybean prices on the domestic market fall below 8.50 baht per
kilogram, the imports will be banned.
</P>
<P>
Imports of fishmeal will face a duty of 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
Local animal feed producers expressed welcome to the new policy
to help them bring down the rising cost of imported raw materials
after the baht depreciated.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
