<HEADLINE> Minister: Ukrainian Army to Survive Through Reorganization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, December 26 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine's armed forces will
survive the country's economic crisis through reorganization and
international cooperation, Defense Minister Alexander Kuzmuk said.
</P>
<P>
"The army needs to be reorganized so it will fit in with
economic realities while remaining capable of protecting the
country's borders," Kuzmuk said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Disarmament and international cooperation have saved money and
improved the army's efficiency, he said, adding "the armed force
have gradually gained prestige both at home and abroad."
</P>
<P>
Once worked in Angola, Ukrainian peacekeepers have been part of
the United Nations contingent in East Slovenia, the multi-national
force in Bosnia; and served as U.N. observers in Tadjikistan.
</P>
<P>
But due to years of sluggish economy, the armed force have been
severely under-funded. In 1997, the military got from the national
budget about 800 million hryvnas (428 million U.S. dollars), 44
percent of what the Defense Ministry asked for.
</P>
<P>
"It's easy to blame the ministry but that won't change
anything," Kuzmuk said. "We've got to find ways of using what
budget we do have efficiently."
</P>
<P>
The Defense Ministry has started to tighten expenditures and
sell off surplus military property, he said. "We've already cut
out more than 500 military structures, which has allowed us to
save considerable sums."
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, another important way out of the
economic difficulties is through disarmament.
</P>
<P>
On December 24, Kuzmuk announced that the number of military
staff will be cut by 75,000 to 400,000 in 1998. Ultimately,
Ukraine's armed forces will number no more than 350,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
