<HEADLINE> Indonesia Unveils New Rules on Bourse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 27 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government
Friday announced the establishment of a stock market custodian and
settlement company, and issued new capital market regulations in a
bid to boost and further secure trading activities on the
country's flagging bourses.
</P>
<P>
Basically, the new rules are aimed at bolstering legal bases
and provide new opportunities to capital market players, Minister
of Finance Mar'ie Muhammad said when he made the announcement.
</P>
<P>
The new company, which will facilitate scripless stock trading
on the Jakarta Stock Exchange, is expected to start early March,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The new regulations introduced asset-backed securities and
Indonesian depository receipts as new instruments in the market.
</P>
<P>
With the issuance of new rules, Mar'ie said, companies wishing
to get fresh funds could sell their nonliquid assets, including
future earnings, to investors through investment managers and
custodian banks.
</P>
<P>
As for investors, asset-backed securities could serve as an
investment instrument alternative.
</P>
<P>
Some of the new regulations are aimed at promoting the
professionalism of stock companies, giving information to the
public, and regulating business mergers and acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
The Jakarta Stock Exchange composite index, the main price
gauge for the Indonesia stock market, dropped 37.86 percent from
638.10 points at the beginning of the year to 396.53 points
recorded Wednesday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
