<HEADLINE> Venezuela Ends Year With 5.1 Percent Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, December 26 (Xinhua) -- Venezuela's economy will
finish 1997 with a registered 5.1 percent growth rate, a big
increase over the 1.6 percent decrease of last year, the Central
Bank said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Inflation had run at an annual rate of 38 percent, much less
than last year's 103.2 percent, said the bank's president, Antonio
Casa Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
He said tax revenue increased 24.5 percent this year, the
highest since 1991.
</P>
<P>
The country's economic growth was boosted by an 8.8 percent
increase in the oil sector, and a 19 percent growth in fixed gross
investments, with an 11.2 and 11.4 percent increases for oil and
non-oil exports respectively.
</P>
<P>
However, Venezuela registered a trade surplus of 11.4 billion
U.S. dollars in 1997 which was less than last year's, due to an
increase of 12.311 billion dollars in imports. 
</P>
