<HEADLINE> Thailand's Listed Firms Suffer Huge Forex Losses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 27 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's listed
non-financial companies are expected to suffer dramatic foreign
exchange losses as a result of the weakening Thai currency,
according to the Nation newspaper Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The combined foreign exchange losses of the 169 such companies
jumped more 75 percent in baht terms this quarter from the last
quarter when it was about 36 baht to the US dollar, compared with
45 in this quarter.
</P>
<P>
Their total foreign exchange losses in the fourth quarter of
the year are estimated at 367 billion baht (8.16 billion US
dollars), as against 207 billion baht (5.75 billion dollars)
during July-September.
</P>
<P>
The losses result from the baht's lower exchange rate against
major foreign currencies, higher funding costs and higher costs in
imported materials.
</P>
<P>
The 169 listed non-financial companies are in all major
industrial sectors, including capital-intensive industries and the
agribusiness.  
</P>
