<HEADLINE> Mexican Government States Strategy for Chiapas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, December 26 (Xinhua) -- A government envoy arrived
in Mexico's southeastern state of Chiapas on Friday with a
four-point strategy aimed at achieving peace with rebels following
the massacre of 45 indigenous people earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
Pedro Joaquin Coldwell said his mission was to "seek closer
ties (with the rebels) to resume a dialogue".
</P>
<P>
In the Chenalho municipality of the state, a gang of masked
gunmen, wielding assault rifles, on Monday killed 21 women, nine
men, 14 children and one infant who were fleeing violence from
other parts of the state.
</P>
<P>
The government believed the assailants were from neighboring
communities that house the Zapatista National Liberation Army, the
country's best-known rebels.
</P>
<P>
One point of the strategy, Coldwell said, was to seek a
rapprochement with the Zapatista rebels to re-open dialogue in the
best conditions.
</P>
<P>
The second point was, with credible investigations, to find and
punish the culprits.
</P>
<P>
Coldwell said the third point was related to the implementation
of preventive actions to avoid the repetition of such incidents.
</P>
<P>
The fourth point was to ratify the political and social
guidelines to remedy the high degree of backwardness and poverty
in the Chiapas state.
</P>
<P>
The Zapatistas rose up on New Year's Day 1994 to demand better
living conditions for the state's impoverished ethnic Maya
majority, and to fight for democratic reform nationwide. Talks
between the government and the Zapatistas broke off in September
1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
