<HEADLINE> Peru Mends Fences With Neighbors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, December 26 (Xinhua) -- Peru strengthened relations with
the neighboring countries and economic blocs during 1997, the
Foreign Ministry said today.
</P>
<P>
The ministry gave priority to political dialogue, consolidation
of border integration programs, and development of proposals of
economic integration and complementary strategies, said sources in
the ministry.
</P>
<P>
Several integration programs were carried out involving
Bolivia, Brazil, Chile, Colombia, Ecuador, Mexico, the United
States, Japan, and China.
</P>
<P>
Relations with Brazil were promoted through the Ilo (Peru)-La
Paz (Bolivia)-Cuiaba (Brazil) corridor.
</P>
<P>
With Colombia, Peru gave priority to drafting the plan for the
integral development of the Putumayo River watershed, which
comprises 14 projects in the border zone.
</P>
<P>
Peru promoted progress in the talks for other integration
processes at a world level, starting with an expanded market
between the Andean Community of Nations and the Southern Common
Market.
</P>
<P>
Peru joined plans to create a free trade zone in all the
continent for the next century.
</P>
<P>
The ministry also started discussions in the past year on a
cooperation program with the European Union during the 1998-2000
period.
</P>
<P>
Dialogue and cooperation mechanisms were promoted to identify
new interests and modalities in Peru's relations with Russia and
the countries of central and eastern Europe, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
An adequate framework created with China to develop bilateral
relations in the commercial and economic fields had contributed to
the expansion of Peru's commerce. China's investments in Peru's
mining and oil exploration industries amounted to 250 million
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Peru joined the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) Forum
in 1997. Its trade exchange with the APEC nations increased 173
percent during the 1990-1996 period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
