<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Economic Slowdown to Hurt Banks in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 27 (Xinhua) -- The expected economic slowdown
next year will surely hurt the Philippines' banking industry since
it will result in higher non-performing loans.
</P>
<P>
Local press Saturday quoted a report by the U.S. investment
bank JP Morgan as saying that the dead loans are expected to move
up to six to seven percent of the total loan portfolio by the end
of 1998 from this year's three percent.
</P>
<P>
This is because more companies will slow down their production
and some others will completely halt expansion as a result of the
currency meltdown and higher interest rates in the country, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
"This notable slowdown in economic growth will certainly impair
the banks' performance," it said.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the report pointed out that the impact of
the economic slowdown will be mitigated by the underlying strength
of the local banks.
</P>
<P>
JP Morgan considered the Philippine banking industry as one of
the "less vulnerable" when compared with those of Thailand,
Malaysia and other countries in Southeast Asia, the report said.
</P>
<P>
JP Morgan also expected the Philippines' gross domestic
product, total goods and services produced inside the country, to
grow by only 2.5 percent next year.
</P>
<P>
However, government economic planners and some economic
analysts said the economy will grow steadily next year.
</P>
<P>
Economic Development Secretary Cielito Habito said the
country's gross national product and gross domestic product will
grow by 4.5 and 4 percent respectively.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
