<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment Increases in Cuba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, December 26 (Xinhua) -- Ibrahim Ferradaz, Cuba's
minister of foreign investment and economic cooperation, said
Friday that more overseas investment flowed into Cuba in 1997 than
before.
</P>
<P>
He described it as a failure of the United States Helms-Burton
law to scare investors away.
</P>
<P>
Ferradaz said Cuba is finishing 1997 with about 300 foreign
capital associations and 160 foreign operators in the duty-free
zones, a big growth over last year's.
</P>
<P>
After the three duty-free zones entered into operation, the
number of requests by new operators continued to increase, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said Cuba signed 30 agreements with other countries in 1997
to promote investments, including 15 signed after the promulgation
of the Helms-Burton law.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the United States hardened its embargo imposed on
Cuba with the Helms-Burton law, which intends to scare foreign
investments by imposing sanctions against companies and
businessmen who would do business with this Caribbean nation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
