<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Dismisses Iraq's Accusation as "Ridiculous" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 26 (Xinhua) -- The United States on
Friday dismissed as "ridiculous" the Iraqi accusation that
Washington was planning air strikes with chemical or biological
weapons.
</P>
<P>
"We term this ridiculous," said a White House spokesman. "We
do not have these weapons in our operational inventory."
</P>
<P>
Iraq's Revolutionary Command Council and the regional Command
of the ruling Baath party held a meeting earlier on Friday,
discussing any possible reprisals from the United States after
Iraq refused to allow U.N. weapons inspectors to enter
presidential areas for checking whether there hide any weapons
of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
An Iraqi official spokesman told the Iraqi news agency INA
after that meeting that Washington was likely to "launch
military strikes on these sites and others, using mass
destruction weapons which contain chemical and biological
elements, so that it can say, after the strikes, that its
allegations were right."
</P>
<P>
Asked if the United States was planning to take air strikes on
Iraq with conventional weapons, without any chemical or biological
component, the White House spokesman said he would have "no
comment on that."
</P>
<P>
The United States has repeatedly warned Iraq that it would
not rule out the use of force if Baghdad does not comply with
U.N. inspections regime. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
